# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acquittal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In common law jurisdictions, an **acquittal** means that the criminal prosecution has failed to prove that the accused is guilty beyond a reasonable doubt of the charge presented.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] It certifies that the accused is free from the charge of an offense, as far as criminal law is concerned.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] The finality of an acquittal is dependent on the jurisdiction.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In some countries, such as the United States, an acquittal prohibits the retrial of the accused for the same offense, even if new evidence surfaces that further implicates the accused.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] The effect of an acquittal on criminal proceedings is the same whether it results from a jury verdict or results from the operation of some other rule that discharges the accused.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In other countries, like Australia, Canada and the UK, the prosecuting authority may appeal an acquittal similar to how a defendant may appeal a conviction — but usually only if new and compelling evidence comes to light or the accused has interfered with or intimidated a juror or witness.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In Canada, the prosecution may appeal different types of decisions, judgments, or orders in criminal cases.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Scots law previously had two acquittal verdicts: *not guilty* and *not proven*.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] However, a verdict of "not proven" did not give rise to the double jeopardy rule.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In England and Wales, which share a common legal system, the Criminal Justice Act 2003 creates an exception to the double jeopardy rule, by providing that retrials may be ordered if "new and compelling evidence" comes to light after an acquittal for a serious crime.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Also, the Criminal Procedure and Investigations Act 1996 permits a "tainted acquittal" to be set aside in circumstances where it is proved beyond reasonable doubt that an acquittal has been obtained by violence or threats of violence to a witness or juror/s.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In modern England and Wales, and in all countries that substantially follow English criminal procedure, an acquittal normally results in the immediate liberation of the defendant from custody, assuming no other charges against the defendant remain to be tried.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] However, until 1774, a defendant acquitted by an English or Welsh court would be remanded to jail until he had paid the jailer for the costs of his confinement.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] It was known for acquitted persons to die in jail for lack of jailer's fees.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] With one exception, the prosecution in the United States cannot appeal an acquittal because of constitutional prohibitions against double jeopardy.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] If the judgment is upon an acquittal, the defendant, indeed, will not seek to have it reversed, and the government cannot.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] A verdict of acquittal, although not followed by any judgment, is a bar to a subsequent prosecution for the same offense.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Society's awareness of the heavy personal strain which a criminal trial represents for the individual defendant is manifested in the willingness to limit the Government to a single criminal proceeding to vindicate its very vital interest in enforcement of criminal laws.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] 141 (1962) that the prosecution cannot appeal a judgment of acquittal by a jury.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] 358 (1975), this was held applicable to bench trials.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] 203 (1984), it was ruled that in a bench trial, when a judge was holding a separate hearing after the jury trial, to decide if the defendant should be sentenced to death or life imprisonment, the judge decided that the circumstances of the case did not permit death to be imposed.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] On appeal, the judge's ruling was found to be erroneous.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] However, even though the decision to impose a life sentence instead of death was based on the judge's incorrect interpretation of the law, the finding of life imprisonment in the original case constituted an acquittal of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Thus, death could not be imposed upon a subsequent trial.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Even though the acquittal of the death penalty was erroneous in that case, the acquittal must stand.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] The only exception to an acquittal being final is if the defendant was never in actual jeopardy.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] If a defendant bribes a judge and obtains acquittal due to a bench trial, the acquittal is invalid because the defendant was never in jeopardy in the first place.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Judges of the Criminal Division, Circuit Court of Cook County, Illinois, et al.*, 138 F.3d 302 (7th Cir.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] An acquittal, while conclusive as to the criminal law, does not necessarily bar private civil actions in tort or on some other grounds as a result of the facts alleged in the charge.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] For example, the City of Los Angeles was held liable in 1994 for the 1991 Rodney King beating despite state acquittals in 1992 of all of its four main LAPD defendants, and in 1997 O.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Simpson was held civilly liable for wrongful death even after being tried and acquitted in 1995 of murder.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] An acquittal also does not bar prosecution for the same offenses under a statute of a different jurisdiction.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] An acquittal does not mean the defendant is innocent of the charge presented—only that the prosecutor failed to prove that the defendant was *guilty beyond a reasonable doubt*.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] The charge may remain on the defendant's criminal record in the United States even after an acquittal, depending on the state regulations.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] A federal criminal record may include acquittals, case dismissals, and convictions.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] In the UK, police forces can reveal whether individuals have been acquitted of criminal charges when issuing information for enhanced record checks, according to a 2018 Supreme Court ruling.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Depending on one's location, a background check may highlight not only convictions or plea bargains but also arrests, charges that were dropped or dismissed, and acquittals.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] Some jurisdictions differentiate between an acquittal that reflects a verdict in favor of a defendant and a "full acquittal" that establishes a defendant's innocence.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] "Not guilty" also refers to a type of plea in a criminal case.
[src:acquittal/acquittal] When multiple charges are filed against a defendant, and a judge or jury finds the defendant not guilty of some charges but guilty of others, the defendant is said to have received a "partial acquittal".
[src:acquittal/acquittal] The defendant will then be sentenced for the charges that did not result in acquittal.
[src:acquittal/appeal] In law, an **appeal** is the process in which cases or decisions are reviewed by a higher authority, where parties request a formal change to an official decision.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Appeals function both as a process for error correction as well as a process of clarifying and interpreting law.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Although appellate courts have existed for thousands of years, common law countries did not incorporate an affirmative right to appeal into their jurisprudence until the 19th century.
[src:acquittal/appeal] "**Appellate review**" is the general term for the process by which courts with appellate jurisdiction exercise jurisdiction over matters decided by lower courts.
[src:acquittal/appeal] It is distinguished from judicial review, which refers to the court's overriding constitutional or statutory right to determine whether a legislative act or administrative decision is defective for jurisdictional or other reasons (which may vary by jurisdiction).
[src:acquittal/appeal] American English and British English have diverged significantly on the topic of appellate terminology.
[src:acquittal/appeal] American cases go up "on appeal" and one "appeals from" (intransitive) or "appeals" (transitive) an order, award, judgment, or conviction, while decisions of British courts are said to be "under appeal" and one "appeals against" a judgment.
[src:acquittal/appeal] In most jurisdictions the normal and preferred way of seeking appellate review is by filing an appeal against the lower court's judgment.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Appellate courts and other systems of error correction have existed for many millennia.
[src:acquittal/appeal] During the first dynasty of Babylon, Hammurabi and his governors served as the highest appellate courts of the land.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Ancient Roman law recognized the right to appeal in the Valerian and Porcian laws since 509 BC.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Later it employed a complex hierarchy of appellate courts, where some appeals would be heard by the emperor.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Additionally, appellate courts have existed in Japan since at least the Kamakura shogunate (1185–1333).
[src:acquittal/appeal] During this time, the shogunate established **hikitsuke**, a high appellate court to aid the state in adjudicating lawsuits.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Although some scholars argue that "the right to appeal is itself a substantive liberty interest", the notion of a right to appeal is a relatively recent advent in common law jurisdictions.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Commentators have observed that common law jurisdictions were particularly "slow to incorporate a right to appeal into either its civil or criminal jurisprudence".
[src:acquittal/appeal] The idea of an appeal from court to court (as distinguished from court directly to the Crown) was unheard of in early English courts.
[src:acquittal/appeal] English common law courts eventually developed the writs of error and certiorari as routes to appellate relief, but both types of writs were severely limited in comparison to modern appeals in terms of availability, scope of review, and remedies afforded.
[src:acquittal/appeal] For example, writs of error were originally not available as a matter of right and were issued only upon the recommendation of the attorney general (which was initially discretionary but by modern times was regularly granted).
[src:acquittal/appeal] Certiorari was originally available only for summary offences; in the early 19th century, certiorari became available for indictable offences, but only to obtain relief before judgment.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Due to widespread dissatisfaction with writs (resulting in the introduction of at least 28 separate bills in Parliament), England switched over to appeals in civil cases in 1873, and in criminal cases in 1907.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Although some courts permit appeals at preliminary stages of litigation, most litigants appeal final orders and judgments from lower courts.
[src:acquittal/appeal] A fundamental premise of many legal systems is that appellate courts review questions of law *de novo*, but appellate courts do not conduct independent fact-finding.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Instead, appellate courts will generally defer to the record established by the trial court, unless some error occurred during the fact-finding process.
[src:acquittal/appeal] In some jurisdictions on the other hand, such as the Netherlands, appellate courts review cases in their entirety, which includes fact-finding.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Many jurisdictions provide a statutory or constitutional right for litigants to appeal adverse decisions.
[src:acquittal/appeal] However, most jurisdictions also recognize that this right may be waived.
[src:acquittal/appeal] In the United States, for example, litigants may waive the right to appeal, as long as the waiver is "considered and intelligent".
[src:acquittal/appeal] The appellate process usually begins when an appellate court grants a party's petition for review or petition for certiorari.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Unlike trials, which many common law jurisdictions typically perform with a jury, appeals are generally presented to a judge, or a panel of judges.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Before hearing oral argument, parties will generally submit legal briefs in which the parties present their arguments at length in writing.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Appellate courts may also grant permission for an *amicus curiae* to submit a brief in support of a particular party or position.
[src:acquittal/appeal] After submitting briefs, parties often have the opportunity to present an oral argument to a judge or panel of judges.
[src:acquittal/appeal] During oral arguments, judges often ask questions to attorneys to challenge their arguments or to advance their own legal theories.
[src:acquittal/appeal] After deliberating in chambers, appellate courts issue formal written opinions that resolve the legal issues presented for review.
[src:acquittal/appeal] The appeal may end with a reversal, in which the lower court's decision is found to be incorrect (resulting in the original judgement being vacated, and the lower court instructed to retry the case) or an affirmation, in which the lower court's decision is found to be correct.
[src:acquittal/appeal] When considering cases on appeal, appellate courts generally affirm, reverse, or vacate the decision of a lower court.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Some courts maintain a dual function, where they consider both appeals and matters of "first instance".
[src:acquittal/appeal] For example, the Supreme Court of the United States primarily hears cases on appeal but retains original jurisdiction over a limited range of cases.
[src:acquittal/appeal] Some jurisdictions maintain a system of intermediate appellate courts, which are subject to the review of higher appellate courts.
[src:acquittal/appeal] The highest appellate court in a jurisdiction is sometimes referred to as a "court of last resort" or supreme court.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] Durant was born Chaya Kaufman in Proskurov, Russian Empire (now Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine), to Jewish parents Ethel Appel Kaufman and Joseph Kaufman.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The family emigrated in 1900, living for several months in London 1900–01 en route to the United States, where they arrived in 1901.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] She had three older sisters, Sarah, Mary, and Flora, and three older brothers, Harry, Maurice, and Michael.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] Flora became Ariel's companion and sometime assistant, and moved with the Durants to California.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] She met her future husband when she was a student at Ferrer Modern School in New York City.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] He was then a teacher at the school, but resigned his post to marry Ariel.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] At the time of the wedding, on October 31, 1913, Ariel was 15 and Will Durant was nearly 28 years old.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The wedding took place at New York City Hall, to which she roller-skated from her family's home in Harlem.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The couple had one daughter, Ethel Benvenuta Durant (1919–1986) and adopted a son, Louis Richard "Lipschultz" Durant (1917–2008) who was the son of Ariel's sister Flora Kaufman Lipschultz and her former husband, Joseph Bernard Lipschultz (divorced 1928).
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] Louis had lived in Will and Ariel's home with his mother, Flora, when he was quite young (1920 Census).
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] Ariel Durant legally changed her first name to Ariel after the character from Shakespeare's *The Tempest*, which was the nickname her husband gave her because he said she was "strong and brave as a boy, and as swift and mischievous as an elf".
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The Durants were awarded the Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction in 1968 for *Rousseau and Revolution*, the tenth volume of *The Story of Civilization*.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] In 1977 they were presented with the Presidential Medal of Freedom by Gerald Ford, and Ariel was named "Woman of the Year" by the city of Los Angeles.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The Durants received the Golden Plate Award of the American Academy of Achievement in 1976.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The Durants wrote a 420-page joint autobiography, published by Simon & Schuster in 1978 (*A Dual Autobiography*; later ISBN 0-671-23078-6).
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] The Durants died within two weeks of each other in 1981, with Ariel dying on October 25 and Will following on November 7. and are buried at the Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery in Los Angeles, California.
[src:acquittal/ariel-durant] Ariel told Ethel's daughter, Monica Mehill, that it was their differences that made them grow.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A **background check** is a process used by an organisation or person to verify that an individual is who they claim to be, and check their past record to confirm education, employment history, and other activities, and for a criminal record.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The frequency, purpose, and legitimacy of background checks vary among countries, industries, and individuals.
[src:acquittal/background-check] An employment background check typically takes place when someone applies for a job, but it can also happen at any time the employer deems necessary.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A variety of methods are used to complete these checks, including comprehensive database search and letters of reference.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Pre-September 11, 2001, background checks were less common and less intrusive.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In the 2000s, background checks became far more common after 9/11.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Government agencies such as the Transportation Security Administration (TSA) and U.S.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Department of Homeland Security were created afterwards to protect national security and safeguard American citizens.
[src:acquittal/background-check] These agencies were tasked with examining airport security, pre-flight screening, and predicting potential terror attacks.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The Federal Bureau of Investigation has a catalogue of DNA, fingerprints, and other means of identification for people with past criminal activity.
[src:acquittal/background-check] There are many types of background checks employers may use to verify a potential new hire.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers often request background checks on job candidates for employment screening, especially for candidates seeking a position that requires high security or a position of trust, such as in a school, courthouse, hospital, financial institution, airport, and government.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Background checks in the corporate realm have become a commonplace practice for many companies, aimed at mitigating legal liabilities and preventing adverse actions within their workforce.
[src:acquittal/background-check] They can also be requested when purchasing a firearm (from a legal authorization).
[src:acquittal/background-check] A government agency traditionally administers these checks for a nominal fee, but private companies can also administer them.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Results of a background check typically include past employment verification, credit history, and criminal history.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The objective of background checks is to ensure the safety and security of the employees in the organization.
[src:acquittal/background-check] These checks are often used by employers as a means of judging a job candidate's past mistakes, character, and fitness, and to identify potential hiring risks for safety and security reasons.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Background checks are also used to thoroughly investigate potential government employees to be given a security clearance.
[src:acquittal/background-check] However, these checks can sometimes be used for illegal purposes, such as unlawful discrimination (or employment discrimination), identity theft, and violation of privacy.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Checks are frequently conducted to confirm information found on an employment application or résumé/curriculum vitae.
[src:acquittal/background-check] One study showed that half of all reference checks done on prospective employees differed between what the job applicant provided and what the source reported.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A 2026 survey by GCheck of job applicants in the United States reported that misrepresentation in applications is relatively common and is associated with perceptions of limited verification, as well as demand for greater transparency in background screening processes.
[src:acquittal/background-check] They are also used to differentiate potential employees further and to select the candidate the employer considers best suited for the position.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers are obligated to ensure their work environment is safe for all employees and helps prevent other employment problems in the workplace.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In the United States under the Gun Control Act of 1968, citizens and US residents must be 18 years or older to purchase shotguns, rifles, or ammunition.
[src:acquittal/background-check] All other firearms – such as handguns – can only be sold to individuals 21 or older.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Restricted firearms (like machine guns), suppressors, explosives or large quantities of precursor chemicals, and concealed weapons permits also require criminal checks.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Checks are also required for those working in positions with special security concerns, such as trucking, ports of entry, and airports (including airline transportation).
[src:acquittal/background-check] Laws exist to prevent those who do not pass a criminal check from working in careers involving the elderly, disabled, or children.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Pre-employment screening refers to the process of investigating the backgrounds of potential employees and is commonly used to verify the accuracy of an applicant's claims as well as to discover any possible criminal history, workers compensation claims, or employer sanctions.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The Brazilian legal system prohibits discrimination against people.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Many people consider background checks to be discriminatory.
[src:acquittal/background-check] It is the responsibility of the employer to treat all personal information collected from the employee as confidential information and to limit the access to this information within the organization.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer cannot retain the personal information from the applicant and must have protective measures in case of data breach.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer must give the applicant the ability to access the personal information being held about them.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Dutch Data Protection Authority must be notified of the background check.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The first Polish research on the issue of pre-employment screening shows that 81% of recruiters have come across the phenomenon of lies in the CVs of candidates for the job.
[src:acquittal/background-check] It is the responsibility of the employer to collect necessary information and to protect it so that only certain people in the organization can access it.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The applicant must receive a copy of the background check so that the applicant has the opportunity to make sure that the information in the background check is correct.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer is not permitted to keep the personal information for a longer period than necessary.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer has to treat the personal information from the applicant as confidential.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The applicant has to receive a copy of the background in order to verify or update the information it contains.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer cannot retain the information more than it is necessary.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer has to give any one who comes in contact with the information of the applicant a code of conduct.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The company has to go through an audit to make sure they are complying and protecting the data.
[src:acquittal/background-check] During the 2008 financial crisis, the level of fraud almost doubled.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Background-checking firm Powerchex claimed the number of applicants lying on their applications increased after the start of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In 2009, Powerchex claimed that nearly one in 5 applicants has a major lie or discrepancy on his or her application.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Almost half (48%) of organizations with fewer than 100 staff experienced problems with vetted employees.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The research shows how many failures occurred in the relationship between employer and employee over the years and what dangers it brings.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Applicants usually lie about additional skills (85%), dates of employment (58%), responsibilities (53%) or positions (28%).
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer must obtain consent from the applicant granting approval of the background check.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employer must be in accordance with the Fair Credit Reporting Act.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The employers have to guarantee that they will not discriminate against the applicant.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Most notably, the Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA) regulates the use of consumer reports (which it defines as information collected and reported by third party agencies) as it pertains to adverse decisions, notification to the applicant, and destruction and safekeeping of records.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Individuals must also consent in order for the employer to obtain a credit report.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Title XLV, section 768.095 of the *Florida Statutes* is a law that allows former employers to disclose information about an employee to a future employer, protecting employers from negligent hiring liabilities.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers use disclosed information from past employers when a background check does not provide enough information on the employee.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers have to verify that the information disclosed to them is true because if it is false, the employer will be violating the civil rights of the employee.
[src:acquittal/background-check] There are a variety of types of investigative searches that can be used by potential employers.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Many commercial sites will offer specific searches to employers for a fee.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Services like these will actually perform the checks, supply the company with adverse action letters, and ensure compliance throughout the process.
[src:acquittal/background-check] It is important to be selective about which pre-employment screening agency one uses.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A legitimate company will maintain a background check policy and will explain the process.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Many employers choose to search the most common records such as criminal records, driving records, and education verification.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Other searches such as sex offender registry, credential verification, skills assessment, reference checks, credit reports and Patriot Act searches are becoming increasingly common.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Larger companies are more likely to outsource than their smaller counterparts – the average staff size of the companies who outsource is 3,313 compared to 2,162 for those who carry out in-house checks.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Financial service firms had the highest proportion of respondents who outsource the service, with over a quarter (26%) doing so, compared to an overall average of 16% who outsource vetting to a third party provider.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The construction and property industry showed the lowest level of outsourcing, with 89% of such firms in the sample carrying out checks in-house, making the overall average 16%.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Companies that choose to outsource must be sure to use companies that are Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA) compliant.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Companies that fail to use an FCRA compliant company may face legal issues.
[src:acquittal/background-check] As a general rule, employers may not take adverse action against an applicant or employee (not hiring or terminating them), solely on the basis of results obtained through a database search.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Database searches, as opposed to source records searches (search of actual county courthouse records), are notoriously inaccurate, contain incomplete or outdated information, and should only be used as an added safety net when conducting a background check.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Failure by employers to follow FCRA guidelines can result in hefty penalties.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In the United States, the employer could use criminal records as verification as long as the employer does not discriminate based on race, color, religion, sex or national origin, as analyzed under the disparate treatment and disparate impact frameworks.
[src:acquittal/background-check] There are several types of criminal record searches available to employers, some more accurate and up to date than others.
[src:acquittal/background-check] These "third party" background checking agencies cannot guarantee the accuracy of their information, thus many of them have incomplete records or inaccurate records.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The only way to conduct an accurate background check is to go directly through the state.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Most times using the state of choice is much cheaper than using a "third party" agency.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Many websites offer the "instant" background check, which will search a compilation of databases containing public information for a fee.
[src:acquittal/background-check] These "instant" searches originate from a variety of sources, from statewide court and corrections records to law enforcement records which usually stem from county or metro law enforcement offices.
[src:acquittal/background-check] There are also other database-type criminal searches, such as statewide repositories and the national crime file.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A commonly used criminal search by employers who outsource is the county criminal search.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers could use social media as tool to conduct a background check on an applicant.
[src:acquittal/background-check] An employer could check the applicant's Facebook, Twitter, and LinkedIn accounts to see how the applicant behaves outside of work.
[src:acquittal/background-check] U.S. employers are legally prohibited from taking into account anything they discover about a person's marital status, sexual orientation, religion, or political views when making the final decision to hire or not hire the applicant.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Some companies provide Media Mentions Reports collected from open sources including Social Media public accounts.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Employers may investigate past employment to verify position and salary information.
[src:acquittal/background-check] More intensive checks can involve interviews with anybody that knew or previously knew the applicant—such as teachers, friends, coworkers, neighbors, and family members; however, extensive hearsay investigations in background checks can expose companies to lawsuits.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Past employment and personal reference verifications are moving toward standardization with most companies in order to avoid expensive litigation.
[src:acquittal/background-check] These usually range from simple verbal confirmations of past employment and timeframe to deeper, such as discussions about performance, activities and accomplishments, and relations with others.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The past experiences and the companies which have provided these experiences are also verified and researched upon to detect frauds.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A fraudulent SSN may be indicative of identity theft, incorrect claims of citizenship status, or concealment of a "past life".
[src:acquittal/background-check] Background screening firms usually perform a Social Security trace to determine where the applicant or employee has lived.
[src:acquittal/background-check] All employers are required to keep government Form I-9 documents on all employees and some states mandate the use of the federal E-Verify program to research the working status of Social Security numbers.
[src:acquittal/background-check] With increased concern for right-to-work issues, many outsourcing companies are sprouting in the marketplace to help automate and store Form I-9 documentation.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Credit checks are conducted for applicants who are applying to positions that deal with financial records or deal with a lot of money.
[src:acquittal/background-check] For example, in the state of Illinois, employers could use an applicant's credit history, only the credit score is considered satisfactory.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Individuals must also give consent in order for the employer to obtain a credit report.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Pre-employment credit reports do not include a credit score.
[src:acquittal/background-check] A pre-employment credit report will show up on an individual's credit report as a "soft inquiry" and do not affect the individual's credit score.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Drug tests and credit checks for employment are highly controversial practices.
[src:acquittal/background-check] According to the Privacy Rights Clearinghouse, a project of the Utility Consumers' Action Network (UCAN): "While some people are not concerned about background investigations, others are uncomfortable with the idea of investigators poking around in their personal histories.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In-depth checks could unearth information that is irrelevant, outdated, taken out of context, or just plain wrong.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In May 2002, allegedly improper post-hire checks conducted by Northwest Airlines were the subject of a civil lawsuit between Northwest and 10,000 of their mechanics.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Except as authorized under subsection (b) of this section, no consumer reporting agency may make any consumer report containing . . .
[src:acquittal/background-check] Civil suits, civil judgments, and records of arrest that from date of entry, antedate the report by more than seven years or until the governing statute of limitations has expired, whichever is the longer period.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Subsection (b) provides for an exception if the report is in connection with "the employment of any individual at an annual salary which equals, or which may reasonably be expected to equal $75,000, or more".
[src:acquittal/background-check] Further controversies to background checks include firearms processing and munitions sales.
[src:acquittal/background-check] As of March 2025, federal law requires background checks be conducted for gun purchases from a gun dealer.
[src:acquittal/background-check] As gun violence across schools and public spaces increase, so does the need to call for better background checks.
[src:acquittal/background-check] Not all states require background checks for handgun purchases however.
[src:acquittal/background-check] To buy a gun, prospective gun owners must submit a background check through the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS).
[src:acquittal/background-check] They then must fill out ATF form 4473 which after, the licensed firearm dealer send this back go NICS.
[src:acquittal/background-check] NICS then do their own background check to verify the other eligibilities to purchase a firearm.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In New Zealand, criminal checks have been affected by the *Criminal Records (Clean Slate) Act 2004*, which allows individuals to legally conceal "less serious" convictions from their records provided they had been conviction-free for at least seven years.
[src:acquittal/background-check] In Michigan, the system of criminal checks has been criticized in a recent case where a shooting suspect was able to pass an FBI check to purchase a shotgun although he had failed the check for a state handgun permit.
[src:acquittal/background-check] The Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence has criticized the federal policy, which denies constitutional rights based on a criminal check only if the subject has been accused of a crime.
[src:acquittal/bail] In other countries, such as the United Kingdom, bail is more likely to consist of a set of restrictions that the defendant will have to abide by for a set period of time.
[src:acquittal/bail] Under this usage, bail can be given both before and after charge.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail offered before charge is known as pre-charge or police bail, to secure the defendant's release under investigation.
[src:acquittal/bail] For minor crimes, a defendant may be summoned to court without the need for bail, or may be released on recognizance (promising to appear in court, with no bail required) following arraignment.
[src:acquittal/bail] For serious crimes, or for defendants who are deemed likely to fail to turn up in court, they may be remanded (detained) while awaiting trial.
[src:acquittal/bail] A defendant is given bail in cases where remand is not justified but there is a need to provide an incentive for the defendant to appear in court.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail amounts may vary depending on the type and severity of crime the defendant is charged with; practices for determining bail amounts vary.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail laws in Australia are similar to the laws of New Zealand and Canada, but are different in each state.
[src:acquittal/bail] Each state holds that there is a *prima facie* entitlement to bail for most charges upon application by a defendant.
[src:acquittal/bail] However, there is an exception when the charges are especially serious, such as drug trafficking, family violence or murder.
[src:acquittal/bail] In such cases, there is no entitlement to bail, and it must be argued as to what circumstances exist that justify a grant of bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] In Victoria, bail may be refused to a defendant who faces a more serious charge unless the defendant demonstrates compelling reasons why bail should be granted.
[src:acquittal/bail] Compelling reasons may generally be established by demonstrating that jail is an unlikely outcome for the charge, or that bail conditions can be imposed that make re-offending unlikely.
[src:acquittal/bail] In cases where a defendant is charged with murder, terrorism or offending with a moderately serious charge while on bail, to become eligible for bail the defendant must prove exceptional circumstances.
[src:acquittal/bail] Exceptional circumstances are difficult to demonstrate, but may arise as a consequence of significant delay in a criminal prosecution.
[src:acquittal/bail] People charged with a criminal offence in Canada have a constitutional right to reasonable bail (referred to as "judicial interim release" in the *Criminal Code*) unless there is some compelling reason to deny it.
[src:acquittal/bail] These reasons can be related to the accused's likelihood to skip bail, or to public danger resulting from the accused being at large.
[src:acquittal/bail] The accused may be denied bail because the public confidence in the administration of justice may be disturbed by letting the individual go free pending the completion of the trial or passing of sentence.
[src:acquittal/bail] Sureties and deposits can be imposed, but are optional.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail can be considered when a charged person is held because of concern of possible escape or of a continuation of criminal activity.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail cannot be considered where there is a concern of influencing witnesses or otherwise frustrating the proceedings.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail is also excluded in case of 31 specified serious crimes (e.g. murder, grievous bodily harm, rape, robbery, public endangerment, etc.) when the person is held due to concern of continuation of criminal activity.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail may be posted either by the charged person, or with his or her consent, by a third party, but this only after this third party has received a thorough briefing regarding the charges and reasons for custody and possible grounds for the forfeiture of the bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] After the bail has been posted, the court must again review the grounds for bail, and must decide either to accept or refuse the bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] When accepting the bail, the court may also require the charged person to stay in the country.
[src:acquittal/bail] The court holds out on bail as long as the reasons for custody remain (which includes pending of the charges), and in case of conviction until the convict starts serving prison sentence, reimburses the criminal proceedings and/or pays court-ordered fine.
[src:acquittal/bail] In case that the court decided also on damages and the aggrieved party asks for it within three months, the bail or its part may be used also to reimburse the damages.
[src:acquittal/bail] Both the prosecutor and the person in custody may challenge any decision on custody (including bail) by filing a complaint which leads to review by an appellate court.
[src:acquittal/bail] The possibility of posting bail is mentioned in passing in § 71, part 3, of the constitution of Denmark.
[src:acquittal/bail] For example, there were seven instances during the period 1973–1987.
[src:acquittal/bail] In France, bail may be ordered by the examining magistrate or the judge of freedoms and detention within the framework of judicial control in French law (before the trial).
[src:acquittal/bail] Indian law stresses the principles of presumption of innocence.
[src:acquittal/bail] The principle embodies freedom from arbitrary detention and serves as a bulwark against punishment before conviction.
[src:acquittal/bail] More importantly, it prevents the State from successfully employing its vast resources to cause greater damage to an un-convicted accused than he/she can inflict on society.
[src:acquittal/bail] While considering bail applications of the accused, courts are required to balance considerations of personal liberty with public interest.
[src:acquittal/bail] Accordingly, the granting of bail should be the rule rather than the exception.
[src:acquittal/bail] The courts have also held that foreign nationals cannot be deprived of the right to seek bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] The *Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973* does not define bail, although the terms bailable offence and non-bailable offence have been defined in section 2(a) of the Code.
[src:acquittal/bail] A Bailable offence is defined as an offence which is shown as bailable in the First Schedule of the Code or which is made bailable by any other law, and non-bailable offence means any other offence.
[src:acquittal/bail] A person who is arrested for a 'bailable' offence may secure bail at the police station, while those who fail to secure police bail and those arrested for non-bailable offences have to secure bail in court.
[src:acquittal/bail] Sections 436 to 450 set out the provisions for the grant of bail and bonds in criminal cases.
[src:acquittal/bail] The amount of security that is to be paid by the accused to secure his release has not been mentioned in the code.
[src:acquittal/bail] Thus, it is left to the discretion of the court to put a monetary cap on the bond.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Supreme Court of India has delivered several cases wherein it has reiterated that the basic rule is – bail and not jail.
[src:acquittal/bail] One such instance came in *State of Rajasthan, Jaipur v.
[src:acquittal/bail] The bench of Krishnaiyer, V.R. had observed that when considering the question of bail, the gravity of the offence involved and the heinousness of the crime which are likely to induce the petitioner to avoid the course of justice must weigh with the court.
[src:acquittal/bail] Taking into consideration the facts of the case the apex court held that the circumstances and the social milieu do not militate against the petitioner being granted bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] When a person accused of a crime is arrested, his statement is recorded and information such as the name, residence address, birthplace, charges filed are noted.
[src:acquittal/bail] The police officer may also check back the criminal record if any in the police station and ask for fingerprints to file a case against the accused.
[src:acquittal/bail] Under the Code of Criminal Procedure 1973 (First Schedule), offences have been classified as "bailable" and "non-bailable" offences.
[src:acquittal/bail] In the case of bailable offences, if the accused produces proper surety, and fulfils other conditions, it is binding upon the Investigating officer to grant bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] However, in case of a non-bailable offence, the police cannot grant bail; it can only be granted by a judicial magistrate/judge.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Investigating Officer must produce the accused before the judicial magistrate/judge concerned within 24 hours of his arrest.
[src:acquittal/bail] At that time, the accused has a right to apply for bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] Depending upon the facts of the case, the judge decides whether bail should be granted.
[src:acquittal/bail] If bail is granted the accused must deposit money with the court.
[src:acquittal/bail] Generally, for lesser crimes, a standard amount is asked to be deposited for awarding the bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] There are some conditions put under section 437 of the Cr.P.C. wherein bail can be requested even for a non-bailable offence.
[src:acquittal/bail] In non-bailable cases, bail is not the right of the accused, but the discretion of the judge if regards the case as fit for the grant of bail, it regards imposition of certain conditions as necessary in the circumstances.
[src:acquittal/bail] Section 437(3) elaborates the conditions set by the law to get bail in non-bailable offences.
[src:acquittal/bail] However, for that, the Court has the power to impose any condition which it considers necessary.
[src:acquittal/bail] In Ireland, bail (Irish: *bannaí*, from Old Norse *band*, "binding") is when a person enters a written bond (recognisance), committing to appear before the court to answer the charges made against them.
[src:acquittal/bail] A person may be required to lodge money as part of their bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] A surety is a person who makes themselves responsible for a defendant coming to court.
[src:acquittal/bail] They promise to pay a sum of money to the court if the defendant does not appear as agreed; however, commercial bail bonding as in the U.S. is illegal.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Sixteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland, approved by referendum in 1996, provided that a court could refuse bail to a person charged with a serious offence where it feared that while at liberty they would commit a serious offence.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Bail Act 1997 was passed by the Oireachtas the following year, and it governs bail in the Republic.
[src:acquittal/bail] In New Zealand, those charged with a criminal offence have a right to be released on bail with reasonable terms and conditions, unless there is a good reason for continuing to be held in custody.
[src:acquittal/bail] When one is arrested the police decide whether to grant the person bail until their court date.
[src:acquittal/bail] After that the courts will have discretion whether to grant bail again, if the case is not resolved at the first court appearance.
[src:acquittal/bail] Certain offences (such as violence, drug-dealing, or repeat offenders) automatically disqualify persons from being granted bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] People who have previously breached their bail or the conditions associated with it are less likely to be granted bail again.
[src:acquittal/bail] In the modern English bail system, monetary payments play a very small role.
[src:acquittal/bail] Securities and sureties can be taken as conditions for being granted bail, but these amounts are not excessive.
[src:acquittal/bail] Wider restrictions such as curfews, electronic monitoring, presenting at a police station, and limits on meeting specific people or going to specific places are more common conditions.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail is regulated primarily by the Bail Act 1976 and the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984, both of which have been heavily amended by later legislation such as the Policing and Crime Act 2017.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Bail Act 1976 was enacted with the aims of creating more conditions by which defendants could be denied bail and also redefining the parameters of fulfilling bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Bail Act also nullified the recognizance system, removing the requirement of paying a specific amount of money and instead arresting defendants for failing to surrender.
[src:acquittal/bail] The Bail Act created a qualified right to be granted bail before conviction, except for when certain factors applied.
[src:acquittal/bail] This does not guarantee a person will get bail, but it places the onus on the prosecution to demonstrate why bail should be refused in preference to custody.
[src:acquittal/bail] Bail can be granted by any of the courts of Scotland, with the final decision in solemn proceedings being with the High Court of Justiciary.
[src:acquittal/bail] All crimes are bailable, and bail should be granted to any accused person "except where there is good reason for refusing bail".
[src:acquittal/bail] (Scotland) Act 2000, an Act of the Scottish Parliament, had removed the previous restrictions on bail that meant that murder and treason were not ordinarily bailable.
[src:acquittal/bail] However, a person could be bailed when accused of these crimes on application of the Lord Advocate or by a decision of the High Court itself.
[src:acquittal/bail] (Reform) (Scotland) Act 2007 reintroduced restrictions on the granting of bail by requiring exceptional circumstances to be shown when a person is accused of a violent, sexual or drugs offence, and they have a prior conviction for a similar offence.
[src:acquittal/bail] In Scotland, the focus is normally for those who are opposed to bail to convince the courts that bail should not be granted, with the procurator fiscal given guidance to use the nature and gravity of an offence as grounds to oppose bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] A person who is refused bail can appeal against the refusal to either the Sheriff Appeal Court for summary proceedings in the Sheriff Courts and Justice of the Peace Courts and solemn proceedings in the Sheriff Courts, or to the High Court of Justiciary when a case is on trial there.
[src:acquittal/bail] The High Court of Justiciary has final authority to decide all bail decisions, and will decide on bail appeals for cases before the High Court on first instance.
[src:acquittal/bail] A Procurator Fiscal or Advocate Depute can request the High Court to review any bail decision where they believe that bail should not have been granted.
[src:acquittal/bail] The 8th Amendment to the United States Constitution states, "Excessive bail shall not be required", thus establishing bail as a constitutionally-protected right.
[src:acquittal/bail] What constitutes "excessive" is a matter of judicial discretion, and bail *can* be denied if the judge feels that it will not aid in forcing the accused back to trial.
[src:acquittal/bail] Money bail is the most common form of bail in the United States and the term "bail" often specifically refers to such a deposit, but other forms of pre-trial release are permitted; this varies by state.
[src:acquittal/bail] Many states have a "bail schedule" that lists the recommended bail amount for a given criminal charge.
[src:acquittal/bail] At the first court appearance (the arraignment), the judge can set the bail at the amount listed on the schedule or at a different amount based on the specific facts of the crime and the person accused.
[src:acquittal/bail] A common criticism of bail in the United States is that the likelihood of a person charged with an offence being released is significantly affected by their economic status and systemic racial bias.
[src:acquittal/bail] Once detained pretrial, these economically disadvantaged people have been shown to experience conditions in jails that improperly induce guilty pleas (whether or not they are factually or legally guilty).
[src:acquittal/bail] In response, in 2014 New Jersey and Alaska abolished cash bail for all but a limited number of court cases; and in 2023, Illinois abolished cash bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] Though the California legislature attempted to eliminate cash bail in 2018, this change was vetoed by California Proposition 25 in November 2020.
[src:acquittal/bail] In 2019, New York passed bail reform legislation that took effect on 1 January 2020, eliminating cash bail for many misdemeanor and non-violent felony charges.
[src:acquittal/bail] However, this law was later narrowed by the governor due to public pushback led by prosecutors and law enforcement officials.
[src:acquittal/bail] In the United States, it is common for bail to be a cash (or other property) deposit.
[src:acquittal/bail] Cash bail in other countries is more limited.
[src:acquittal/bail] Known as a bail bond or cash bail, an amount of money is posted so that the person charged with an offence can be released from pre-trial detention.
[src:acquittal/bail] Unless posted by a bail bondsman, this deposit is refunded if the person makes all of their required court appearances.
[src:acquittal/bail] In 46 US states, a commercial bail bondsman can be paid to deposit bail money on behalf of a detained individual.
[src:acquittal/bail] This practice is mostly illegal in the rest of the world.
[src:acquittal/bail] In Germany, the use of bail bondsmen is legal if the court allows it in its decision to grant cash bail.
[src:acquittal/bail] Illinois, Kentucky, Oregon, and Wisconsin have outlawed commercial bail bonds, while New Jersey and Alaska rarely permit money bail.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] A **bench trial** is a trial by judge, as opposed to a jury.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] The term applies most appropriately to any administrative hearing in relation to a summary offense to distinguish the type of trial.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Many legal systems (Roman, Islamic) use bench trials for most or all cases or for certain types of cases.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] As a jury renders a verdict, in a bench trial, a judge does the same by making a finding.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Most civil trials proceed without a jury and are heard by a judge sitting alone.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Summary criminal trials may be heard by a single district judge (magistrates' court) or by a panel of at least two, but more usually three, magistrates.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Section 47 of the Criminal Justice Act 2003 allows a bench trial for indictable offences, but is rarely used, having been exercised only twice since its inception.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Most civil trials in Scotland are conducted in a sheriff court by a sheriff sitting alone.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In the Court of Session, a judge in either the outer or inner house usually sits alone; but may sit with a jury in certain trials such as personal injury claims.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Summary criminal trials are conducted by a sheriff in a sheriff court or a justice of the peace in the justice of the peace court sitting alone as regulated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Those trials requiring juries are called solemn procedure and are also regulated under the Act.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] One of the recommendations of the Commission of Inquiry 2008–2009 in Turks and Caicos was that provisions be made for criminal trials without juries, following the precedent in England and Wales.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Other examples cited included the United States, the Commonwealth of Nations including India and Canada, the British overseas territories of the Falkland Islands and St.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In United States law, for most criminal cases that proceed to trial, trial by jury is usually a matter of course as it is a constitutional right under the Sixth Amendment and cannot be waived without certain requirements.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In the federal court system, under Rule 23 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, if a defendant is entitled to a jury trial, the trial must be by jury unless the defendant waives a jury trial in writing.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In the various state court systems, waiver of jury trial can vary by jurisdiction.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Missouri has Missouri Supreme Court Rule 27.01(b), "The defendant may, with the assent of the court, waive a trial by jury and submit the trial of any criminal case to the court..."; the prosecution needs not consent.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] With bench trials, the judge plays the role of the jury as finder of fact in addition to making conclusions of law.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In some bench trials, both sides have already stipulated to all the facts in the case (such as civil disobedience cases designed to test the constitutionality of a law).
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Because of needing fewer formalities, these cases are usually faster than jury trials.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] For example, there is no jury selection phase and no need for sequestration or jury instructions.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] A bench trial (whether criminal or civil) that is presided over by a judge has some distinctive characteristics, but it is similar to a jury trial.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] For example, the rules of evidence and methods of objection are the same in a bench trial as in a jury trial.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Bench trials, however, are frequently less formal than jury trials.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] It is often less necessary to protect the record with objections, and sometimes evidence is accepted *de bene* or provisionally, subject to the possibility of being struck in the future.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] All trials in India since 1973 are heard by a judge or a division bench of judges.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] The main reason for the abolishment of jury trial in India was due to a popular case K.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] Nanavati vs State of Maharashtra, in which the jury gave a verdict of not guilty even when all the evidence was present against the accused, resulting in a jury nullification.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] In most countries with "Roman law" or civil law, there is no "jury" in the English sense, and trials are necessarily bench trials.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] However, in more complicated cases, lay judges can be called.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] They are not randomly selected, as juries are.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] They are professional, although not legally trained as jurists, and vote as judges.
[src:acquittal/bench-trial] One notable exception, from French law, is cour d'assises, where jurors are allotted and vote alongside professional judges.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] In criminal law, **Blackstone's ratio** is the ratio between letting guilty go unpunished (error of impunity) and convicting innocent people, two forms of miscarriage of justice.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] There is also a long history of similar sentiments going back centuries in a variety of legal traditions.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] The idea subsequently became a staple of legal thinking in jurisdictions with legal systems derived from English criminal law and continues to be a topic of debate.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] In the United States, high courts in individual states continue to adopt different numerical values for the ratio.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] The phrase was absorbed by the British legal system, becoming a maxim by the early 19th century.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] It was also absorbed into American common law, cited repeatedly by that country's Founding Fathers, later becoming a form of words drilled into law students all the way into the 21st century.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Other commentators have echoed the principle.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Benjamin Franklin stated it as: "it is better 100 guilty Persons should escape than that one innocent Person should suffer".
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] The immediate precursors of Blackstone's ratio in English law were articulations by Hale (about 100 years earlier) and John Fortescue (about 300 years before Blackstone), both influential jurists in their time.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Hale wrote: "for it is better five guilty persons should escape unpunished, than one innocent person should die." Fortescue's *De Laudibus Legum Angliae* (c.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Islamic scholar Al-Tirmidhi quotes Muhammad as saying, "Avoid legal punishments as far as possible, and if there are any doubts in the case then use them, for it is better for a judge to err towards leniency than towards punishment".
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] A similar expression reads, "Invoke doubtfulness in evidence during prosecution to avoid legal punishments".
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] A vaguely similar principle, echoing the number ten and the idea that it would be preferable that many guilty people escape consequences than a few innocents suffer them, appears as early as the narrative of Sodom and Gomorrah in Genesis.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Cullerne Bown has argued that both the rise and fall in significance of the Ratio can be explained by the growing mathematisation of society.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] It rises to prominence at about the same time as Cesare Beccaria articulated the social principle of the greatest good for the greatest number, the starting point for Utilitarianism and, like the Ratio, quantitative in a loose way.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] From a mathematical point of view, the Ratio is methodologically flawed, and once the Ratio lost its claim to the authority of mathematics, its usefulness declined.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Today, its former role in justifying the policies of the criminal courts is primarily occupied by Herbert L.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Packer's Two Models theory, an expanded doctrine of rights and arguments drawn from law and economics.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Blackstone's principle influenced the nineteenth-century emergence of the "beyond a reasonable doubt" standard in criminal law.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Many modern commentators draw a connection between the familiar "ten guilty persons" ratio and a specific probability threshold in criminal trials.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Empirical research supports the idea that numerical guidelines may affect jurors' decisions.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Clark Stanton (1985) show that mock juries presented with explicit percentages or probabilities demonstrate more consistent verdicts than those relying solely on verbal definitions of "beyond a reasonable doubt".
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] While some legal theorists remain cautious about expressing the burden of proof in mathematically precise terms, proponents argue that quantification aligns closely with the historical logic of Blackstone's ratio and helps clarify the meaning of reasonable doubt for fact-finders.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] The Blackstone's ratio can be represented as the false negative to false positive ratio.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] Opinion polls in the US found a majority of people view false acquittal and false conviction as equally bad, resulting in a Blackstone's ratio of one.
[src:acquittal/blackstone-s-ratio] "I'm more concerned with bad guys who got out and released than I am with a few that in fact were innocent." Asked whether the 25% margin was too high, Cheney responded, "I have no problem as long as we achieve our objective. ...
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Also, in some cases, acts of recidivism, aggravated robbery, and kidnapping, in addition to drug trafficking, drug dealing, and drug possession, are capital crimes or enhancements.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] However, states have also imposed punitive executions for an expansive range of conduct, for political or religious beliefs and practices, for a status beyond one's control, or without employing any significant due process procedures.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Judicial murder is the intentional and premeditated killing of an innocent person by means of capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] For example, the executions following the show trials in the Soviet Union during the Great Purge of 1936–1938 were an instrument of political repression.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] As of 2021, 55 countries retain capital punishment, 108 countries have taken a position to abolish it *de jure* for all crimes, 8 have abolished it for ordinary crimes (while maintaining it for special circumstances such as war crimes), and 28 are abolitionist in practice.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Although the majority of countries have abolished capital punishment, over half of the world's population lives in countries where the death penalty is retained.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] As of 2023, only 2 out of 38 OECD member countries (the United States and Japan) allow capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Capital punishment is controversial, with many people, organisations, religious groups, and states holding differing views on its ethical permissibility.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the European Union (EU), the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union prohibits the use of capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Council of Europe, which has 46 member states, has worked to end the death penalty; no execution has taken place in its current member states since 1997.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The United Nations General Assembly has adopted, throughout the years from 2007 to 2020, eight non-binding resolutions calling for a global moratorium on executions, with support for eventual abolition.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Nearly all societies in human history have executed criminals and dissidents since the beginning of civilization.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Until the nineteenth century, without developed prison systems, there was frequently no workable alternative to ensure deterrence and incapacitation of criminals.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Other methods which appear only in legend include the blood eagle and brazen bull.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The use of formal execution extends to the beginning of recorded history.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Most historical records and various primitive tribal practices indicate that the death penalty was a part of their justice system.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Communal punishments for wrongdoing generally included blood money compensation by the wrongdoer, corporal punishment, shunning, banishment, and execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In tribal societies, compensation and shunning were often considered sufficient as forms of justice.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The response to crimes committed by neighbouring tribes, clans, or communities included a formal apology, compensation, blood feuds, and tribal warfare.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] A blood feud or vendetta occurs when arbitration between families or tribes fails, or an arbitration system is nonexistent.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] This form of justice was common before the emergence of an arbitration system based on the state or organized religion.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] It may result from crime, land disputes, or a code of honour.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In most countries that practice capital punishment, it is now reserved for murder, terrorism, war crimes, espionage, treason, or as part of military justice.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In many countries that use the death penalty, drug trafficking and often drug possession are also capital offences.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In China, human trafficking and serious cases of corruption and financial crimes are punished by the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In militaries around the world, courts-martial have imposed death sentences for offences such as cowardice, desertion, insubordination, and mutiny.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Elaborations of tribal arbitration of feuds included peace settlements, often conducted in a religious context, as well as compensation systems.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Compensation was based on the principle of *substitution*, which might include material compensation (for example, cattle, enslaved people, land), the exchange of brides or grooms, or the payment of blood debt.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Settlement rules could allow for animal blood to replace human blood, or transfers of property or blood money, or, in some cases, an offer of a person for execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The person offered for execution did not have to be the original perpetrator of the crime because the social system was based on tribes and clans, not individuals.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Blood feuds could be regulated at meetings, such as the Norsemen *things*.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Systems deriving from blood feuds may survive alongside more advanced legal systems or be given recognition by courts (for example, trial by combat or blood money).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] One of the more modern refinements of the blood feud is the duel.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In certain parts of the world, nations emerged as ancient republics, monarchies, or tribal oligarchies.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Common linguistic, religious, or family ties often united these nations.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Moreover, the expansion of these nations often occurred through the conquest of neighbouring tribes or nations.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Consequently, various classes of royalty, nobility, various commoners, and enslaved people emerged.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Accordingly, the systems of tribal arbitration were subsumed into a more unified system of justice, which formalized relations among the different "social classes" rather than "tribes".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The earliest and most famous example is the Code of Hammurabi, which prescribed different punishments and compensation based on the classes or groups of victims and perpetrators.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Torah/Old Testament lays down the death penalty for murder, kidnapping, practicing magic, violation of the Sabbath, blasphemy, and a range of sexual crimes, although evidence suggests that actual executions were exceedingly rare, if they occurred at all.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Describing punishment in the Persian empire, Herodotus mentions approvingly that no one, not even an enslaved person, can be executed for only a single crime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] A Peshotanu was a condemned person in Persia.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The word draconian derives from Draco's laws.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Romans also used the death penalty for a wide range of offences.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Protagoras (whose thought is reported by Plato) criticised the principle of revenge, because once the damage is done, it cannot be cancelled by any action.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] So, if the death penalty is to be imposed by society, it is only to protect society against the criminal or for a dissuasive purpose.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] "The only right that Protagoras knows is therefore human right, which, established and sanctioned by a sovereign collectivity, identifies itself with positive or the law in force of the city.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Plato saw the death penalty as a means of purification, because crimes were a "defilement".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Thus, in the Laws, he considered it necessary to execute the animal or destroy the object that caused the death of a man by accident.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] For the murderers, he considered that the act of homicide was not natural and was not fully consented to by the criminal.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Homicide is thus a disease of the soul, which must be reeducated as much as possible, and, as a last resort, sentenced to death if no rehabilitation is possible.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] According to Aristotle, for whom free will is proper to man, a person is responsible for their actions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] If there was a crime, a judge must determine the penalty, allowing the crime to be annulled by compensation.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] This is how pecuniary compensation appeared for criminals, the least recalcitrant, and whose rehabilitation was deemed possible.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] However, for others, he argued, the death penalty is necessary.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] This philosophy aims, on the one hand, to protect society and, on the other, to compensate for the consequences of the crime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] It influenced Western criminal law until the 17th century, when the first reflections on abolishing the death penalty emerged.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Twelve Tables, the body of laws handed down from archaic Rome, prescribe the death penalty for a variety of crimes, including libel, arson, and theft.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] During the Late Republic, there was consensus among the public and legislators to reduce the incidence of capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] This opinion led to voluntary exile being prescribed in place of the death penalty, whereby a convict could either choose to leave in exile or face execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] A historic debate, followed by a vote, took place in the Roman Senate to decide the fate of Catiline's allies when he attempted to seize power in December, 63 BC.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Cicero, then Roman consul, argued in support of the killing of conspirators without judgment by decision of the Senate (Senatus consultum ultimum) and was supported by the majority of senators; among the minority voices opposed to the execution, the most notable was Julius Caesar.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The custom was different for foreigners who did not hold rights as Roman citizens, and especially for enslaved people, who were transferrable property.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Crucifixion was a form of punishment first employed by the Romans against enslaved people who rebelled, and throughout the Republican era was reserved for enslaved people, bandits, and traitors.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Intended to be a punishment, a humiliation, and a deterrent, the condemned could take up to a few days to die.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Corpses of the crucified were typically left on the crosses to decompose and to be eaten by animals.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] There was a time in the Tang dynasty (618–907) when the death penalty was abolished.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] This was in the year 747, enacted by Emperor Xuanzong of Tang (r.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] When abolishing the death penalty, Xuanzong ordered his officials to refer to the nearest regulation by analogy when sentencing those found guilty of crimes for which the prescribed punishment was execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Thus, depending on the severity of the crime, a punishment of severe scourging with the thick rod or exile to the remote Lingnan region might take the place of capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] However, the death penalty was restored only 12 years later in 759 in response to the An Lushan Rebellion.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] At this time in the Tang dynasty, only the emperor had the authority to sentence criminals to execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Under Xuanzong, capital punishment was relatively infrequent, with only 24 executions in the year 730 and 58 executions in the year 736.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The two most common forms of execution in the Tang dynasty were strangulation and decapitation, which were the prescribed methods of execution for 144 and 89 offences, respectively.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Strangulation was the prescribed sentence for lodging an accusation against one's parents or grandparents with a magistrate, scheming to kidnap a person and sell them into slavery, and opening a coffin while desecrating a tomb.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Decapitation was the method of execution prescribed for more serious crimes such as treason and sedition.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Some further forms of capital punishment were practiced in the Tang dynasty, of which the first two that follow at least were extralegal.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The first of these was scourging to death with the thick rod which was common throughout the Tang dynasty, especially in cases of gross corruption.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The second was truncation, in which the convicted person was cut in two at the waist with a fodder knife and then left to bleed to death.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] A further form of execution called Ling Chi (slow slicing), or death by/of a thousand cuts, was used from the close of the Tang dynasty (around 900) to its abolition in 907.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] When a minister of the fifth grade or above received a death sentence, the emperor might grant him a special dispensation allowing him to commit suicide in lieu of execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Even when this privilege was not granted, the law required that the condemned minister be provided with food and ale by his keepers and transported to the execution ground in a cart rather than having to walk there.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Nearly all executions under the Tang dynasty took place in public as a warning to the population.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The heads of the executed were displayed on poles or spears.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] When local authorities decapitated a convicted criminal, the head was boxed and sent to the capital as proof of identity and that the execution had taken place.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In medieval and early modern Europe, before the development of modern prison systems, the death penalty was also used as a generalised form of punishment for even minor offences.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In early modern Europe, a mass panic regarding witchcraft swept across Europe and later the European colonies in North America.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] During this period, there were widespread claims that malevolent Satanic witches were operating as an organised threat to Christendom.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] As a result, tens of thousands of women were prosecuted for witchcraft and executed through the witch trials of the early modern period (between the 15th and 18th centuries).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The death penalty also targeted sexual offences such as sodomy.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the early history of Islam (7th–11th centuries), there is a number of "purported (but mutually inconsistent) reports" (*athar*) regarding the punishments of sodomy ordered by some of the early caliphs.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Other medieval Muslim leaders, such as the Abbasid caliphs in Baghdad (most notably al-Mu'tadid), were often cruel in their punishments.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In early modern England, the Buggery Act 1533 stipulated hanging as punishment for "buggery".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] James Pratt and John Smith were the last two Englishmen to be executed for sodomy in 1835.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 1636 the laws of Puritan governed Plymouth Colony included a sentence of death for sodomy and buggery.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Massachusetts Bay Colony followed in 1641.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Throughout the 19th century, U.S. states repealed death sentences from their sodomy laws, with South Carolina being the last to do so in 1873.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] As People of the Book, Christians under Muslim rule were subjected to *dhimmi* status (along with Jews, Samaritans, Gnostics, Mandeans, and Zoroastrians), which was inferior to the status of Muslims.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Christians unable to pay these taxes were forced to surrender their children to Muslim rulers as payment, who would enslave them in Muslim households where they were forced to convert to Islam.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Many Christian martyrs were executed under the Islamic death penalty for defending their Christian faith through dramatic acts of resistance such as refusing to convert to Islam, repudiation of the Islamic religion and subsequent reconversion to Christianity, and blasphemy towards Muslim beliefs.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Despite the widespread use of the death penalty, calls for reform were not unknown.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Maimonides's concern was maintaining popular respect for law, and he saw errors of commission as much more threatening than errors of omission.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] While during the Middle Ages the expiatory aspect of the death penalty was taken into account, this is no longer the case under the Lumières.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] These define the place of man within society no longer according to a divine rule, but as a contract established at birth between the citizen and society; it is the social contract.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] From that moment on, capital punishment should be seen as useful to society through its dissuasive effect, but also as a means of protection of the latter vis-à-vis criminals.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the last several centuries, with the emergence of modern nation states, justice came to be increasingly associated with the concept of natural and legal rights.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The period saw an increase in standing police forces and permanent penitential institutions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In England, Jeremy Bentham, the founder of modern utilitarianism, called for the abolition of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Beccaria, and later Charles Dickens and Karl Marx noted the incidence of increased violent criminality at the times and places of executions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Official recognition of this phenomenon led to executions being carried out inside prisons, away from public view.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In England in the 18th century, when there was no police force, Parliament drastically increased the number of capital offences to more than 200.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] These were mainly property offences, such as cutting down a cherry tree in an orchard.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 1820, there were 160, including crimes such as shoplifting, petty theft, or stealing cattle.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The severity of the so-called Bloody Code was often tempered by juries who refused to convict, or judges, in the case of petty theft, who arbitrarily set the value stolen at below the statutory level for a capital crime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In Nazi Germany, there were three types of capital punishment; hanging, decapitation, and death by shooting.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Also, modern military organisations employed capital punishment as a means of maintaining military discipline.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the past, cowardice, absence without leave, desertion, insubordination, shirking under enemy fire, and disobeying orders were often crimes punishable by death (see decimation and running the gauntlet).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] One method of execution, since firearms came into common use, has also been the firing squad, although some countries use execution with a single shot to the head or neck.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Various authoritarian states have employed the death penalty as a potent means of political oppression.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Anti-Soviet author Robert Conquest claimed that more than one million Soviet citizens were executed during the Great Purge of 1936 to 1938, almost all by a bullet to the back of the head.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Mao Zedong publicly stated that "800,000" people had been executed in China during the Cultural Revolution (1966–1976).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Partly as a response to such excesses, civil rights organisations started to place increasing emphasis on the concept of human rights and the abolition of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Abolition was often adopted due to political change, as when countries shifted from authoritarianism to democracy, or when it became an entry condition for the EU.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The United States is a notable exception: some states have had bans on capital punishment for decades, while others still actively use it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Notably, in 1846, Michigan became the first government in the United States and also the first ever in the entire Anglosphere to abolish the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The death penalty in the United States remains a contentious issue, which is hotly debated.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In retentionist countries, the debate is sometimes revived when a miscarriage of justice has occurred, though this tends to cause legislative efforts to improve the judicial process rather than to abolish the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In abolitionist countries, the debate is sometimes revived by particularly brutal murders, though few countries have brought it back after abolishing it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] However, a spike in serious, violent crimes, such as murders or terrorist attacks, has prompted some countries to effectively end the moratorium on the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Since then, Pakistan has executed over 400 convicts.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 2017, two major countries, Turkey and the Philippines, saw their executives making moves to reinstate the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the same year, passage of the law in the Philippines failed to obtain the Senate's approval.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 724 AD, during the reign of Emperor Shōmu, the death penalty was banned in Japan, but the abolition lasted only a few years.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 818, Emperor Saga abolished the death penalty under the influence of Shinto and it lasted until 1156.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In China, the death penalty was banned by Emperor Xuanzong of Tang in 747, replacing it with exile or scourging.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Following his conversion to Christianity in 988, Vladimir the Great abolished the death penalty in Kyivan Rus', along with torture and mutilation; corporal punishment was also seldom used.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In England, a public statement of opposition was included in The Twelve Conclusions of the Lollards, written in 1395.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the post-classical Republic of Poljica, life was ensured as a basic right in its Poljica Statute of 1440.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Sir Thomas More's *Utopia*, published in 1516, debated the benefits of the death penalty in dialogue form, coming to no firm conclusion.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] More was himself executed for treason in 1535.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] More recent opposition to the death penalty stemmed from the book of the Italian Cesare Beccaria *Dei Delitti e Delle Pene* ("On Crimes and Punishments"), published in 1764.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In this book, Beccaria aimed to demonstrate not only the injustice, but even the futility from the point of view of social welfare, of torture and the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Influenced by the book, Grand Duke Leopold II of Habsburg, the future emperor of the Holy Roman Empire, abolished the death penalty in the then-independent Grand Duchy of Tuscany, the first abolition in modern times.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] On 30 November 1786, after having *de facto* blocked executions (the last was in 1769), Leopold promulgated the reform of the penal code that abolished the death penalty and ordered the destruction of all the instruments for capital execution in his land.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 2000, Tuscany's regional authorities instituted an annual holiday on 30 November to commemorate the event.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The event is commemorated on this day by 300 cities worldwide, celebrating Cities for Life Day.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Leopold's brother Joseph, then emperor of the Holy Roman Empire, abolished capital punishment in his immediate lands in 1787, a measure that lasted only until 1795, after both had died.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Leopold's son Francis abolished it in his immediate lands.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In Tuscany, it was reintroduced in 1790 after Leopold's departure as emperor.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Only after 1831 was capital punishment again stopped, though it took until 2007 to abolish capital punishment in Italy completely.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The Kingdom of Tahiti was the first legislative assembly in the world to abolish the death penalty in 1824.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Tahiti commuted the death penalty to banishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the United States, Michigan was the first state to ban the death penalty in 1846.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The short-lived revolutionary Roman Republic banned capital punishment in 1849.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Venezuela followed suit and abolished the death penalty in 1863, and San Marino did so too in 1865, however the last execution in San Marino had taken place in 1468.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In Portugal, after legislative proposals in 1852 and 1863, the death penalty was abolished in 1867.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The last execution in Brazil was in 1876; from then on, all the condemnations were commuted by the Emperor Pedro II until its abolition for civil offences and military offences in peacetime in 1891.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] The penalty for crimes committed in peacetime was reinstated and abolished twice (1938–1953 and 1969–1978), but on those occasions, it was restricted to acts of terrorism or subversion considered "internal warfare", and all sentences were commuted and not carried out.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Many countries have abolished capital punishment either in law or in practice.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Since World War II, there has been a trend toward abolishing capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the United States, between 1972 and 1976, the death penalty was declared unconstitutional based on the *Furman v.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Georgia* case once again permitted the death penalty under certain circumstances.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Further limitations were placed on the death penalty in *Atkins v.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Virginia* (2002; death penalty unconstitutional for people with an intellectual disability) and *Roper v.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Simmons* (2005; death penalty unconstitutional if defendant was under age 18 at the time the crime was committed).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the United States, 23 of the 50 states and Washington, D.C. ban capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In the United Kingdom, it was abolished for murder (leaving only treason, piracy with violence, arson in royal dockyards, and some wartime military offences as capital crimes) for a five-year experiment in 1965 and permanently in 1969, the last execution having taken place in 1964.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] It was abolished for all offences in 1998.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Protocol 13 to the European Convention on Human Rights, first entering into force in 2003, prohibits the death penalty in all circumstances for those states that are parties to it, including the United Kingdom from 2004.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] Abolition occurred in Canada in 1976 (except for some military offences, with complete abolition in 1998); in France in 1981; and in Australia in 1973 (although the state of Western Australia retained the penalty until 1984).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In South Australia, under the premiership of then-Premier Dunstan, the *Criminal Law Consolidation Act 1935* (SA) was modified so that the death sentence was changed to life imprisonment in 1976.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p01] In 1977, the United Nations General Assembly affirmed in a formal resolution that throughout the world, it was desirable to "progressively restrict the number of offences for which the death penalty might be imposed, with a view to the desirability of abolishing this punishment".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Most nations, including almost all developed countries, have abolished capital punishment either in law or in practice; notable exceptions are the United States, Japan, Taiwan, and Singapore.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Additionally, capital punishment is also carried out in China, India, and most Islamic states.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to Amnesty International, 20 countries are known to have performed executions in 2022.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] There are countries which do not publish information on the use of capital punishment, most significantly China and North Korea.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to Amnesty International, around 1,000 prisoners were executed in 2017.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Amnesty reported in 2004 and 2009 that Singapore and Iraq, respectively, had the world's highest per capita execution rate.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to Al Jazeera and UN Special Rapporteur Ahmed Shaheed, Iran has had the world's highest per capita execution rate.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A 2012 EU report from the Directorate-General for External Relations' policy department pointed to Gaza as having the highest per capita execution rate in the MENA region.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The use of the death penalty is becoming increasingly restrained in some retentionist countries including Taiwan and Singapore.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Indonesia carried out no executions between November 2008 and March 2013.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Singapore, Japan and the United States are the only developed countries that are classified by Amnesty International as 'retentionist' (South Korea is classified as 'abolitionist in practice').
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Nearly all retentionist countries are situated in Asia, Africa and the Caribbean.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The only retentionist country in Europe is Belarus and in March 2023 Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko signed a law which allows to use capital punishment against officials and soldiers convicted of high treason.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] During the 1980s, the democratisation of Latin America swelled the ranks of abolitionist countries.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This was soon followed by the overthrow of the communist states in Europe.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Many of these countries aspired to enter the EU, which strictly requires member states not to practice the death penalty, as does the Council of Europe (see Capital punishment in Europe).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Public support for the death penalty in the EU varies.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The last execution in a member state of the present-day Council of Europe took place in 1997 in Ukraine.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In contrast, rapid industrialisation in Asia has seen an increase in the number of developed countries which are also retentionist.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In these countries, the death penalty retains strong public support, and the matter receives little attention from the government or the media; in China, there is a small but significant and growing movement to abolish the death penalty altogether.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This trend has been followed by some African and Middle Eastern countries where support for the death penalty remains high.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Some countries have resumed practising the death penalty after having previously suspended the practice for long periods.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The United States suspended executions in 1972 but resumed them in 1976; there was no execution in India between 1995 and 2004; and Sri Lanka declared an end to its moratorium on the death penalty on 20 November 2004, although it has not yet performed any further executions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The Philippines re-introduced the death penalty in 1993 after abolishing it in 1987, but again abolished it in 2006.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The United States and Japan are the only developed countries to have recently carried out executions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The U.S. federal government, the U.S. military, and 27 states have a valid death penalty statute, and over 1,400 executions have been carried out in the United States since it reinstated the death penalty in 1976.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Japan, 98 inmates were executed between January 2000 and July 2022.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] After serial killer Ryuji Kobayashi, who murdered 2 college students by burying alive in Okayama prefecture in 2006, committed suicide at Osaka Detention House on 31 January 2026, Japan had 103 inmates on death row.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] As of May 2025, the most recent country to abolish the death penalty was Zimbabwe on 31 December 2024, almost twenty years after the last execution in the country.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to an Amnesty International report released in April 2020, Egypt ranked regionally third and globally fifth among the countries that carried out the most executions in 2019.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The country has increasingly ignored international human rights concerns and criticism.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In March 2021, Egypt executed 11 prisoners in a jail, who were convicted in cases of "murder, theft, and shooting".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to Amnesty International's 2021 report, at least 483 people were executed in 2020 despite the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The figure excluded countries that classify death penalty data as state secrets.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The top five executioners for 2020 were China, Iran, Egypt, Iraq, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Public opinion on the death penalty varies considerably by country and by the crime in question.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Countries where a majority of people are against execution include Norway, where only 25% support it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Most French, Finns, and Italians also oppose the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2020, 55% of Americans supported the death penalty for an individual convicted of murder, down from 60% in 2016, 64% in 2010, 65% in 2006, and 68% in 2001.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2020, 43% of Italians expressed support for the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Taiwan, polls and research have consistently shown strong support for the death penalty at 80%.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This includes a 2016 survey conducted by the National Development Council of Taiwan, which found that 88% of Taiwanese people oppose abolishing the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Its continuation of the practice drew criticism from local rights groups.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The support and sentencing of capital punishment has been growing in India in the 2010s due to anger over several recent brutal cases of rape, even though actual executions are comparatively rare.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] While support for the death penalty for murder is still high in China, executions have dropped precipitously, with 3,000 executed in 2012 versus 12,000 in 2002.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A poll in South Africa, where capital punishment is abolished, found that 76% of millennial South Africans support the re-introduction of the death penalty due to increasing incidents of rape and murder.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A 2017 poll found that younger Mexicans were more likely to support capital punishment than older ones.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] 57% of Brazilians support the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The age group that shows the greatest support for the execution of those condemned is the 25 to 34-year-old category, in which 61% say they support it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A 2023 poll by Research Co. found that 54% of Canadians support reinstating the death penalty for murder in their country.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In April 2021 a poll found that 54% of Britons said they would support reinstating the death penalty for those convicted of terrorism in the UK, while 23% of respondents said they would be opposed.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2020, an Ipsos/Sopra Steria survey showed that 55% of the French people support the reintroduction of the death penalty; this was an increase from 44% in 2019.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty for juvenile offenders (criminals aged under 18 years at the time of their crime, although the legal or accepted definition of *juvenile offender* may vary from one jurisdiction to another) has become increasingly rare.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] China, Pakistan, the United States, Saudi Arabia, and Yemen have since raised the minimum age to 18.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Amnesty International has recorded 61 verified executions since then, in several countries, of both juveniles and adults who had been convicted of committing their offences as juveniles.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] China does not allow for the execution of those under 18, but child executions have reportedly taken place.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] One of the youngest children ever to be executed was the infant son of Perotine Massey on or around 18 July 1556.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] His mother was one of the Guernsey Martyrs who were executed for heresy, and his father had previously fled the island.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] At less than one day old, he was ordered to be burned by Bailiff Hellier Gosselin, with the advice of priests nearby who said the boy should burn due to having inherited moral stain from his mother, who had given birth during her execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Since 1642 in Colonial America and in the United States, an estimated 365 juvenile offenders were executed by various colonial authorities and (after the American Revolution) the federal government.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Supreme Court abolished capital punishment for offenders under the age of 16 in *Thompson v.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Oklahoma* (1988), and for all juveniles in *Roper v.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Prussia, children under the age of 14 were exempted from the death penalty in 1794.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Capital punishment was cancelled by the Electorate of Bavaria in 1751 for children under the age of 11 and by the Kingdom of Bavaria in 1813 for children and youth under 16 years.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Prussia, the exemption was extended to youth under the age of 16 in 1851.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] For the first time, all juveniles were excluded from the death penalty by the North German Confederation in 1871, which was continued by the German Empire in 1872.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Nazi Germany, capital punishment was reinstated for juveniles between 16 and 17 years in 1939.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This was broadened to include children and youth aged 12 to 17 in 1943.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty for juveniles was abolished by West Germany, also generally, in 1949 and by East Germany in 1952.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In the Hereditary Lands, Austrian Silesia, Bohemia, and Moravia within the Habsburg monarchy, capital punishment for children under 11 was no longer permitted by 1770.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty was also abolished for juveniles in 1787, except for emergency or military law, which is unclear regarding those.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] It was reintroduced for juveniles above 14 years by 1803, and was raised by general criminal law to 20 years in 1852 and this exemption and the alike one of military law in 1855, which may have been up to 14 years in wartime, were also introduced into all of the Austrian Empire.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In the Helvetic Republic, the death penalty for children and youth under the age of 16 was abolished in 1799 yet the country was already dissolved in 1803, whereas the law could remain in force if it were not replaced on the cantonal level.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In the canton of Bern, all juveniles were exempted from the death penalty at least in 1866.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Fribourg, capital punishment was generally, including for juveniles, abolished by 1849.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Ticino, it was abolished for youth and young adults under 20 in 1816.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Zurich, the exclusion from the death penalty was extended for juveniles and young adults up to 19 years of age by 1835.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 1942, the death penalty was almost deleted in criminal law, as well for juveniles, but since 1928 persisted in military law during wartime for youth above 14 years.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] If no earlier change was made in the given subject, by 1979, juveniles could no longer be subject to the death penalty in military law during wartime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Between 2005 and May 2008, Iran, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, and Yemen were reported to have executed child offenders, the largest number occurring in Iran.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] During Hassan Rouhani's tenure as president of Iran from 2013 until 2021, at least 3,602 death sentences have been carried out.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This includes the executions of 34 juvenile offenders.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child, which forbids capital punishment for juveniles under article 37(a), has been signed by all countries and subsequently ratified by all signatories except the United States (despite the US Supreme Court decisions abolishing the practice).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The UN Sub-Commission on the Promotion and Protection of Human Rights maintains that the death penalty for juveniles has become contrary to a jus cogens of customary international law.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A majority of countries are also party to the U.N.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (whose Article 6.5 also states that "Sentence of death shall not be imposed for crimes committed by persons below eighteen years of age...").
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] But on 10 February 2012, Iran's parliament changed controversial laws relating to the execution of juveniles.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Under the new legislation, the age of 18 (solar year) would apply to both genders, and juvenile offenders must be sentenced pursuant to a separate law specifically addressing juveniles.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Based on Islamic law, which now seems to have been revised, girls at the age of 9 and boys at 15 of the lunar year (11 days shorter than a solar year) are deemed fully responsible for their crimes.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Iran accounted for two-thirds of the global total of such executions, and currently has approximately 140 people considered as juveniles awaiting execution for crimes committed (up from 71 in 2007).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The past executions of Mahmoud Asgari, Ayaz Marhoni and Makwan Moloudzadeh became the focus of Iran's child capital punishment policy and the judicial system that hands down such sentences.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2023 Iran executed a minor who had knifed a man that fought him for following a girl in the street.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Saudi Arabia also executes criminals who were minors at the time of the offence.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2013, Saudi Arabia was the center of an international controversy after it executed Rizana Nafeek, a Sri Lankan domestic worker, who was believed to have been 17 years old at the time of the crime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Saudi Arabia banned executions for minors, except for terrorism cases, in April 2020.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Japan has not executed juvenile criminals since August 1997, when they executed Norio Nagayama, a spree killer who had been convicted of shooting four people dead in the late 1960s.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Nagayama's case gave rise to the eponymous *Nagayama standards*, which consider factors such as the number of victims, brutality, and the social impact of the crimes.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The standards have been used in determining whether to apply the death sentence in murder cases.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Teruhiko Seki, convicted of murdering four family members, including a 4-year-old daughter, and raping a 15-year-old daughter of a family in 1992, became the second inmate to be hanged for a crime committed as a minor in the first such execution in 20 years after Nagayama on 19 December 2017.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Takayuki Otsuki, who was convicted of raping and strangling a 23-year-old woman and subsequently strangling her 11-month-old daughter to death on 14 April 1999, when he was 18, is another inmate sentenced to death; his request for retrial has been rejected by the Supreme Court of Japan.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] There is evidence that child executions are taking place in parts of Somalia controlled by the Islamic Courts Union (ICU).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In October 2008, a girl, Aisha Ibrahim Dhuhulow, was buried up to her neck at a football stadium, then stoned to death in front of more than 1,000 people.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Somalia's established Transitional Federal Government announced in November 2009 (reiterated in 2013) that it plans to ratify the Convention on the Rights of the Child.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This move was lauded by UNICEF as a welcome attempt to secure children's rights in the country.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A public execution is a form of capital punishment which "members of the general public may voluntarily attend".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This definition excludes the presence of a small number of witnesses randomly selected to ensure executive accountability.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Additionally, it afforded the public a chance to witness "what was considered a great spectacle".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Social historians note that beginning in the 20th century in the U.S. and western Europe, death in general became increasingly shielded from public view, occurring more and more behind the closed doors of the hospital.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Executions were likewise moved behind the walls of the penitentiary.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The last formal public executions occurred in 1868 in Britain, in 1936 in the U.S., and in 1939 in France.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] According to Amnesty International, in 2012, "public executions were known to have been carried out in Iran, North Korea, Saudi Arabia and Somalia".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] There have been reports of public executions carried out by state and non-state actors in Hamas-controlled Gaza, Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan, and Yemen.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Executions which can be classified as public were also carried out in the U.S. states of Florida and Utah as of 1992.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Atrocity crimes such as war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide are usually punishable by death in countries retaining capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This tradition is carried on by the current International Criminal Court.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Intentional homicide is punishable by death in most countries retaining capital punishment, but generally, it involves an aggravating factor required by statute or judicial precedents.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In October 2018 the Malaysian Government imposed a moratorium on all executions until the passage of a new law that would abolish the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In April 2023, legislation abolishing the mandatory death penalty was passed in Malaysia.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty would be retained, but courts have the discretion to replace it with other punishments, including whipping and imprisonment of 30–40 years.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In 2018, at least 35 countries retained the death penalty for drug trafficking, drug dealing, drug possession, and related offences.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] People had been regularly sentenced to death and executed for drug-related offences in China, Indonesia, Iran, Malaysia, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, and Vietnam.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Other countries may retain the death penalty for symbolic purposes.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty was mandated for drug trafficking in Singapore and Malaysia.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Notably, drug couriers like Yong Vui Kong and Cheong Chun Yin successfully applied to have their death sentences replaced with life imprisonment and 15 strokes of the cane in 2013 and 2015 respectively.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Death penalty opponents regard the death penalty as inhumane and criticize it for its irreversibility.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] They argue also that capital punishment lacks deterrent effect, or has a brutalization effect, discriminates against minorities and the poor, and that it encourages a "culture of violence".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] There are many organizations worldwide, such as Amnesty International, and country-specific, such as the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU), whose main purpose includes abolition of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Capital punishment for non-lethal crimes is usually considerably more controversial and has been abolished in many of the countries that retain it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Supporters of the death penalty argued that death penalty is morally justified when applied in murder especially with aggravating elements such as for murder of police officers, child murder, torture murder, multiple homicide and mass killing such as terrorism, massacre and genocide.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This argument is strongly defended by New York Law School's Professor Robert Blecker, who says that the punishment must be painful in proportion to the crime.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Eighteenth-century philosopher Immanuel Kant defended a more extreme position, according to which every murderer deserves to die on the grounds that loss of life is incomparable to any penalty that allows them to remain alive, including life imprisonment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Some abolitionists argue that retribution is simply revenge and cannot be condoned.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Others, while accepting retribution as an element of criminal justice, nonetheless argue that life without parole is a sufficient substitute.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Abolitionists believe capital punishment is the worst violation of human rights, because the right to life is the most important, and capital punishment violates it without necessity and inflicts on the condemned a psychological torture.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Human rights activists oppose the death penalty, calling it "cruel, inhuman and degrading punishment".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Amnesty International considers it to be "the ultimate irreversible denial of Human Rights".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In one of the most recent cases relating to the death penalty in Singapore, activists like Jolovan Wham, Kirsten Han and Kokila Annamalai and even the international groups like the United Nations and European Union argued for Malaysian drug trafficker Nagaenthran K.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] They also cited international law, where a country should prohibit the execution of mentally and intellectually impaired people to push for Singapore to commute Nagaenthran's death penalty to life imprisonment based on the protection of human rights.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Despite the international outcry, Nagaenthran was executed on 27 April 2022.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Trends in most of the world have long been to move to private and less painful executions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] France adopted the guillotine for this reason in the final years of the 18th century, while Britain banned hanging, drawing, and quartering in the early 19th century.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Hanging by turning the victim off a ladder or by kicking a stool or a bucket, which causes death by strangulation, was replaced by long drop "hanging" where the subject is dropped a longer distance to dislocate the neck and sever the spinal cord.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar, Shah of Persia (1896–1907) introduced throat-cutting and blowing from a gun (close-range cannon fire) as quick and relatively painless alternatives to more torturous methods of executions used at that time.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In the United States, electrocution and gas inhalation were introduced as supposedly more humane alternatives to hanging, though these have been almost entirely superseded by lethal injection.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A small number of countries, for example, Iran and Saudi Arabia, still employ slow hanging methods, decapitation, and stoning.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The rate of these "botched executions" remained steady over the period of the study.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A separate study published in *The Lancet* in 2005 found that in 43% of cases of lethal injection, the blood level of hypnotics was insufficient to guarantee unconsciousness.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Gross*) that lethal injection does not constitute cruel and unusual punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] It is frequently argued that capital punishment leads to miscarriage of justice through the wrongful execution of innocent persons.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Many people have been proclaimed innocent victims of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Some have claimed that as many as 39 executions have been carried out in the face of compelling evidence of innocence or serious doubt about guilt in the US from 1992 through 2004.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Newly available DNA evidence prevented the pending execution of more than 15 death row inmates during the same period in the US, but DNA evidence is only available in a fraction of capital cases.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] As of 2017, 159 prisoners on death row have been exonerated by DNA or other evidence, which is seen as an indication that innocent prisoners have almost certainly been executed.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty claims that between 1976 and 2015, 1,414 prisoners in the United States were executed, while 156 sentenced to death had their death sentences vacated.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Improper procedure may also result in unfair executions.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] For example, Amnesty International argues that in Singapore, "the Misuse of Drugs Act contains a series of presumptions which shift the burden of proof from the prosecution to the accused.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This conflicts with the universally guaranteed right to be presumed innocent until proven guilty".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Urine drug screenings can be given at the discretion of police, without requiring a search warrant.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The onus is on the accused in all of the above situations to prove that they did not have or consume illegal drugs.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Some prisoners have volunteered or attempted to expedite capital punishment, often by waiving all appeals.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Prisoners have made requests or committed further crimes in prison as well.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In the United States, execution volunteers constitute approximately 11% of prisoners on death row.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Volunteers often bypass legal procedures, which are designed to impose the death penalty for the "worst of the worst" offenders.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Opponents of execution volunteering cited the prevalence of mental illness among volunteers, comparing it to suicide.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Execution volunteers have received considerably less attention and effort at legal reform than those who were exonerated after execution.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Researchers have shown that white Americans are more likely to support the death penalty when told that it is mostly applied to black Americans, and that more stereotypically black-looking or dark-skinned defendants are more likely to be sentenced to death if the case involves a white victim.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Alabama in 2019, a death row inmate named Domineque Ray was denied his imam in the room during his execution, instead only being offered a Christian chaplain.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] After filing a complaint, a federal court of appeals ruled 5–4 against Ray's request.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The majority cited the "last-minute" nature of the request, and the dissent argued that the treatment violated the core principle of denominational neutrality.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In July 2019, two Shia men, Ali Hakim al-Arab, 25, and Ahmad al-Malali, 24, were executed in Bahrain, despite protests from the United Nations and rights groups.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Amnesty International stated that the executions were being carried out on confessions of "terrorism crimes" that were obtained through torture.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Earlier, there were appeals made to advocate for Abdul Kahar's death penalty to be commuted to life imprisonment on humanitarian grounds, as Abdul Kahar came from a low-income family and had struggled with drug addiction.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Both the European Union (EU) and Amnesty International criticised Singapore for finalizing and carrying out Abdul Kahar's execution, and about 400 Singaporeans protested against the government's use of the death penalty merely days after Abdul Kahar's death sentence was authorised.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Still, over 80% of the public supported the use of the death penalty in Singapore.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The United Nations introduced a resolution during the General Assembly's 62nd session in 2007 calling for a universal ban.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The approval of a draft resolution by the Assembly's third committee, which deals with human rights issues, voted 99 to 52, with 33 abstentions, in support of the resolution on 15 November 2007 and was put to a vote in the Assembly on 18 December.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Again in 2008, a large majority of states from all regions adopted, on 20 November in the UN General Assembly (Third Committee), a second resolution calling for a moratorium on the use of the death penalty; 105 countries voted in support of the draft resolution, 48 voted against, and 31 abstained.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The moratorium resolution has been presented for a vote each year since 2007.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] On 15 December 2022, 125 countries voted in support of the moratorium, with 37 opposing and 22 abstaining.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The countries voting against the moratorium included the United States, People's Republic of China, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] A range of amendments proposed by a small minority of pro-death penalty countries were overwhelmingly defeated.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] It had, in 2007, passed a non-binding resolution (by 104 to 54, with 29 abstentions) by asking its member states for "a moratorium on executions with a view to abolishing the death penalty".
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Many regional conventions prohibit the death penalty, most notably, Protocol 6 (abolition in time of peace) and Protocol 13 (abolition in all circumstances) to the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The same is also stated under Protocol 2 in the American Convention on Human Rights, which, however, has not been ratified by all countries in the Americas, most notably Canada and the United States.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Most relevant operative international treaties do not require its prohibition for cases of serious crime, most notably, the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] This instead has, in common with several other treaties, an optional protocol prohibiting capital punishment and promoting its wider abolition.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Several international organizations have made the abolition of the death penalty (during peacetime or in all circumstances) a requirement for membership, most notably the EU and the Council of Europe.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The Council of Europe is willing to accept a moratorium as an interim measure.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Thus, while Russia was a member of the Council of Europe, and the death penalty remains codified in its law, it has not made use of it since becoming a member of the Council – Russia has not executed anyone since 1996.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Except for Russia (abolitionist in practice) and Belarus (retentionist), all European countries are classified as abolitionists.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Latvia abolished *de jure* the death penalty for war crimes in 2012, becoming the last EU member to do so.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Protocol 13 to the European Convention on Human Rights calls for the abolition of the death penalty in all circumstances (including for war crimes).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The majority of European countries have signed and ratified it.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Some European countries have not done this, but all of them, except Belarus, have now abolished the death penalty in all circumstances (*de jure*, and Russia *de facto*).
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Armenia is the most recent country to ratify the protocol, on 19 October 2023.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Protocol 6, which prohibits the death penalty during peacetime, has been ratified by all members of the Council of Europe.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] It had been signed but not ratified by Russia at the time of its expulsion in 2022.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In Turkey, over 500 people were sentenced to death after the 1980 Turkish coup d'état.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] About 50 of them were executed, the last one on 25 October 1984.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Then there was a *de facto* moratorium on the death penalty in Turkey.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] As part of its move towards EU membership, Turkey has made some legal changes.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The death penalty was removed from peacetime law by the National Assembly in August 2002.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In May 2004, Turkey amended its constitution to abolish capital punishment in all circumstances.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] It ratified Protocol 13 to the European Convention on Human Rights in February 2006.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] As a result, Europe is a continent free of the death penalty in practice, all states, having ratified Protocol 6 to the European Convention on Human Rights, with the exceptions of Russia (which has entered a moratorium) and Belarus, which are not members of the Council of Europe.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe has been lobbying for Council of Europe observer states that practice the death penalty, the U.S., and Japan, to abolish it or lose their observer status.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] In addition to banning capital punishment for EU member states, the EU has also banned detainee transfers in cases where the receiving party may seek the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Sub-Saharan African countries that have recently abolished the death penalty include Burundi, which abolished the death penalty for all crimes in 2009, and Gabon which did the same in 2010.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] On 5 July 2012, Benin became part of the Second Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), which prohibits the use of the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The newly created South Sudan is among the 111 UN member states that supported the resolution passed by the United Nations General Assembly that called for the removal of the death penalty, therefore affirming its opposition to the practice.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] South Sudan, however, has not yet abolished the death penalty and has stated that it must first amend its Constitution, and until that happens, it will continue to use the death penalty.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Among non-governmental organizations (NGOs), Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch are noted for their opposition to capital punishment.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] Many such NGOs, as well as trade unions, local councils, and bar associations, formed a World Coalition Against the Death Penalty in 2002.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The world's major faiths have differing views depending on the religion, denomination, sect and the individual adherent.
[src:acquittal/capital-punishment-p02] The Catholic Church considers the death penalty "inadmissible" in any circumstance and denounces it as an "attack" on the "inviolability and dignity of the person." Both the Baháʼí and Islamic faiths support capital punishment.
